Becton, Dickinson and Company (BDX) is Sitrin Capital Management LLC’s 3rd Largest Position

Posted by Dan Jones on Jul 24th, 2017 // No Comments 

Sitrin Capital Management LLC lowered its position in Becton, Dickinson and Company (NYSE:BDX) by 0.6% during the first quarter, according to its most recent 13F filing with the Securities and Exchange Commission (SEC). The institutional investor owned 32,289 shares of the medical instruments supplier’s stock after selling 204 shares during the period. Becton, Dickinson and accounts for approximately 4.3% of Sitrin Capital Management LLC’s holdings, making the stock its 3rd largest position. Sitrin Capital Management LLC’s holdings in Becton, Dickinson and were worth $5,923,000 as of its most recent filing with the SEC. 
Other institutional investors also recently added to or reduced their stakes in the company. Dimensional Fund Advisors LP raised its position in Becton, Dickinson and by 7.0% in the fourth quarter. Dimensional Fund Advisors LP now owns 446,583 shares of the medical instruments supplier’s stock worth $73,934,000 after buying an additional 29,376 shares in the last quarter. Elkfork Partners LLC bought a new position in Becton, Dickinson and during the fourth quarter worth about $4,640,000. Richard C. Young & CO. LTD. acquired a new stake in shares of Becton, Dickinson and during the fourth quarter worth $205,000. Aviva PLC raised its stake in shares of Becton, Dickinson and by 46.6% in the fourth quarter. Aviva PLC now owns 255,426 shares of the medical instruments supplier’s stock worth $42,291,000 after buying an additional 81,181 shares in the last quarter. Finally, Asset Management One Co. Ltd. raised its stake in shares of Becton, Dickinson and by 1,331.7% in the fourth quarter. Asset Management One Co. Ltd. now owns 373,412 shares of the medical instruments supplier’s stock worth $61,838,000 after buying an additional 347,331 shares in the last quarter. 75.48% of the stock is currently owned by hedge funds and other institutional investors. 




Shares of Becton, Dickinson and Company (NYSE:BDX) traded down 0.30% on Monday, hitting $204.68. The company had a trading volume of 502,802 shares. The stock has a market cap of $43.66 billion, a PE ratio of 33.99 and a beta of 1.05. Becton, Dickinson and Company has a 12 month low of $161.29 and a 12 month high of $205.44. The company has a 50-day moving average of $195.21 and a 200 day moving average of $184.45. 


 Get Becton Dickinson and Company alerts:



Becton, Dickinson and (NYSE:BDX) last issued its quarterly earnings results on Tuesday, May 2nd. The medical instruments supplier reported $2.30 EPS for the quarter, topping the consensus estimate of $2.23 by $0.07. Becton, Dickinson and had a net margin of 10.67% and a return on equity of 25.37%. The company had revenue of $2.97 billion during the quarter, compared to analysts’ expectations of $2.92 billion. During the same quarter in the previous year, the company earned $2.18 EPS. Becton, Dickinson and’s revenue was down 3.2% on a year-over-year basis. Analysts anticipate that Becton, Dickinson and Company will post $9.45 EPS for the current fiscal year. 
The firm also recently declared a quarterly dividend, which was paid on Friday, June 30th. Stockholders of record on Friday, June 9th were given a dividend of $0.73 per share. This represents a $2.92 annualized dividend and a dividend yield of 1.42%. The ex-dividend date was Wednesday, June 7th. Becton, Dickinson and’s dividend payout ratio is 48.26%. 
